# MediPredict Web Application Walkthrough

The MediPredict AI Web Application has been successfully implemented with a modern, responsive, and premium medical aesthetic. 

## Accomplished Features

* **Project Setup**: Initialized a Vite React + TypeScript project with routing (`react-router-dom`) and Lucide React icons.
* **Core Styling System**: Created a comprehensive CSS variable system ([index.css](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/src/index.css)) establishing a clean white and medical blue theme, complete with modern typography (Inter font), shadow utilities, and component classes.
* **Layout & Navigation**: 
  * Responsive navigation bar ([Navbar.tsx](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/src/components/Navbar.tsx)) with a mobile drawer toggle.
  * Shared [Layout.tsx](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/src/components/Layout.tsx) for consistent page structures.
* **Pages Implementation**:
  1. **Home Page ([Home.tsx](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/src/pages/Home.tsx))**: An impressive hero section with dynamic medical scan animations, statistics displays, and a breakdown of "Why Choose MediPredict?".
  2. **Eye Disease Information ([DiseaseInfo.tsx](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/src/pages/DiseaseInfo.tsx))**: A structured grid explaining the 16 distinct eye conditions the AI can detect.
  3. **AI Detection Core App ([AIDetection.tsx](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/src/pages/AIDetection.tsx))**: 
     * Drag-and-drop file upload zone for accepting fundus images.
     * Integrates directly with your backend (`POST http://127.0.0.1:8000/predict`).
     * Dynamically renders results in a medical report card, displaying top predictions with progress bars. 
     * Includes buttons to generate downloadable **PDF reports** (via `html2pdf.js`) and save results to the user profile.
  4. **AI Assistant ([AIAssistant.tsx](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/src/pages/AIAssistant.tsx))**: A specialized mockup chat interface designed for vision health queries.
  5. **Patient Profile ([Profile.tsx](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/src/pages/Profile.tsx))**: Reads from `localStorage` to display a historical record of all past AI scans.

## Architecture Restructuring & Bug Fixes

* **Project Structure**: Organized the application precisely matching the user's requested layout:
  * `backend/`: Fast API backend files ([main.py](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/Backend/main.py), [predict.py](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/Backend/predict.py), `models/`, `uploads/`).
  * `frontend/`: The full Vite React TS codebase, nicely contained.
  * `dataset/`, `research/`, [README.md](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/README.md), etc.
* **API Bug Fix**: Resolved the `TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'map')` issue by refactoring [Backend/predict.py](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/Backend/predict.py). It now properly parses probability arrays and returns exactly `top_predictions` list formatted with `disease` and `confidence` properties, which perfectly aligns with the frontend's expected [ApiResponse](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/frontend/src/api/predictAPI.ts#6-12) interface.
* **Component Extraction**: Cleaned up the large `AIDetection` component by extracting [UploadBox.tsx](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/frontend/src/components/UploadBox.tsx), [ResultCard.tsx](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/frontend/src/components/ResultCard.tsx), [ChatUI.tsx](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/frontend/src/components/ChatUI.tsx), and a standalone API file at [predictAPI.ts](file:///c:/Users/prash/Desktop/MediPredict/frontend/src/api/predictAPI.ts).

## Verification & Tests

* **Compilation**: We resolved all strict TypeScript errors and ran `npm run build` which verified that the application compiles perfectly with **0 errors**.
* **Responsive Layouts**: Constructed with native Flexbox and CSS Grid breakpoints ensuring full functionality on mobile, tablet, and desktop environments.

## How to Run

1. Make sure your Python backend is running at `http://127.0.0.1:8000` and has **CORS** enabled.
2. Open a terminal in the `MediPredict` folder.
3. Run `npm run dev` to start the frontend server.
4. Open the displayed local link (usually `http://localhost:5173`) in your browser.
